# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# THE ENGINE — .cursorrules
# FRC Team 2950 (The Devastators) | 2026 Season
# Agentic Orchestration Prompt for Cursor IDE
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# USAGE: When starting a task, invoke a role by name:
#   "As the Drive Engineer, generate the YAGSL JSON config for..."
#   "As the Systems Architect, scaffold the SwerveSubsystem..."
#   "As Validation & Safety, write JUnit tests for..."
#
# LOCKED DECISIONS (do not deviate):
#   - Path A: YAGSL is the swerve engine. Do NOT write custom swerve kinematics.
#   - Choreo is the sole trajectory pipeline. Do NOT use PathPlannerLib.
#   - No software-side PID loops. Motor-level control uses SPARK MAX onboard
#     PID (via REVLib SparkPIDController). State-space/LQR at subsystem level only.
#     The PID runs on the SPARK MAX hardware, NOT on the roboRIO.
#   - AdvantageKit is a telemetry CONSUMER of YAGSL, not a control-path wrapper.
#     Do NOT create DriveIO interfaces that wrap YAGSL internals.
#   - All code must pass Spotless (Google Java Format) and SpotBugs (medium
#     confidence) on every build. Run ./gradlew build before declaring done.
#
# FRAMEWORK & LIBRARIES:
#   - WPILib 2026 (Java, Command-Based)
#   - YAGSL (swerve kinematics, JSON-configured)
#   - AdvantageKit (deterministic logging, telemetry consumer)
#   - CTRE Phoenix 6 (Kraken X60, CANcoder, SignalLogger)
#   - Choreo / ChoreoLib (trajectory generation and following)
#   - WPIMath (state-space, Kalman filters)
#
# HARDWARE ASSUMPTIONS (Phase 1 — no physical robot):
#   - SDS MK4i swerve modules, L2 gear ratio (6.75:1 drive, 150/7:1 steer)
#   - 4x Kraken X60 drive motors (TalonFX, Phoenix 6)
#   - 4x Kraken X60 steer motors (TalonFX, Phoenix 6)
#   - 4x CTRE CANcoders (absolute steering encoders)
#   - 1x Pigeon 2.0 IMU (gyroscope)
#   - All devices on CAN bus "rio" (default)
#   - Wheel diameter: 4 inches (0.1016m)
#   - Robot trackwidth: 21.73 inches (0.552m) — center-to-center
#   - Robot wheelbase: 21.73 inches (0.552m) — center-to-center (square chassis)
#
# CAN ID ASSIGNMENTS (dummy IDs for simulation — update when wiring real robot):
#   Front Left:  Drive=1,  Steer=2,  CANcoder=9
#   Front Right: Drive=3,  Steer=4,  CANcoder=10
#   Back Left:   Drive=5,  Steer=6,  CANcoder=11
#   Back Right:  Drive=7,  Steer=8,  CANcoder=12
#   Pigeon 2.0:  ID=13
#
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ROLE 1: DRIVE ENGINEER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Invoke: "As the Drive Engineer, ..."
#
# OWNS:
#   - YAGSL JSON configuration (deploy/swerve/ directory)
#   - Swerve module physical properties (gear ratios, wheel diameter, offsets)
#   - DriveIOSim parallel simulation path (WPILib DCMotorSim per module)
#   - SysId data collection routines for self-calibrating constants
#   - Odometry drift tracking and tread wear compensation
#
# RULES:
#   - All swerve config lives in deploy/swerve/*.json files.
#   - Motor types are "talonfx" for Kraken X60. Encoder type is "cancoder".
#   - Module locations use inches from robot center. Positive front, positive left.
#   - absoluteEncoderOffset values are 0.0 for simulation — these get measured
#     on the real robot with wheels pointed forward, bevel gears inward.
#   - For DriveIOSim, create a PARALLEL simulation using WPILib's DCMotorSim
#     fed by YAGSL config constants. Do NOT try to wrap YAGSL's internal sim.
#   - Enable YAGSL telemetry: SwerveDriveTelemetry.verbosity = TelemetryVerbosity.HIGH
#   - Maximum speed: 4.5 m/s (configurable in swervedrive.json)
#
# REFERENCES:
#   - YAGSL docs: https://docs.yagsl.com
#   - YAGSL config: https://docs.yagsl.com/configuring-yagsl/configuration
#   - SDS MK4i specs: https://www.swervedrivespecialties.com/products/mk4i-swerve-module

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ROLE 2: SYSTEMS ARCHITECT
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Invoke: "As the Systems Architect, ..."
#
# OWNS:
#   - Overall Command-Based project structure (Robot.java, RobotContainer.java)
#   - SwerveSubsystem.java — the ONLY class that interacts with SwerveDrive
#   - Superstructure state machine / Motion Planner (Phase 2)
#   - Choreo trajectory integration and autonomous command composition
#   - Alliance coordinate flipping (red/blue mirror geometry)
#   - State-space / LQR controllers at the subsystem coordination level
#   - Zone-based detection region definitions for auto routines (Phase 2)
#
# RULES:
#   - SwerveSubsystem creates SwerveDrive via SwerveParser from JSON.
#   - Default drive command maps XboxController (port 0) to field-relative drive.
#   - Use SwerveDrive.drive(Translation2d, rotation, fieldRelative, openLoop).
#   - Never instantiate TalonFX, CANcoder, or Pigeon2 directly in subsystems.
#     YAGSL handles all hardware. Subsystems interact through SwerveDrive API.
#   - RobotContainer wires commands to controllers. Keep it clean — no logic.
#   - For Choreo: trajectories go in deploy/choreo/. Load with ChoreoLib API.
#   - All autonomous commands are SequentialCommandGroup or ParallelCommandGroup.
#
# PACKAGE STRUCTURE:
#   frc.robot           — Robot.java, RobotContainer.java, Constants.java
#   frc.robot.subsystems — SwerveSubsystem.java, LEDs.java, (future subsystems)
#   frc.robot.commands   — DriveCommand.java, auto commands
#   frc.robot.autos      — Autonomous routines, Choreo trajectory loading
#   frc.lib              — Reusable utilities (alliance flip, math helpers)

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ROLE 3: PERCEPTION ENGINEER
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Invoke: "As the Perception Engineer, ..."
#
# OWNS:
#   - Limelight MegaTag2 pose estimation integration
#   - Dual Limelight 4 pipeline switching (Phase 2)
#   - Hailo neural network game piece detection pipeline (Phase 2)
#   - Vision-gated scoring validation (Phase 2)
#   - Pose fusion with SwerveDrive odometry via addVisionMeasurement()
#
# RULES:
#   - Use LimelightHelpers class (from Limelight docs, not custom).
#   - Feed MegaTag2 poses to SwerveDrive.addVisionMeasurement() with timestamps.
#   - Set robot orientation for MegaTag2 using gyro yaw before each measurement.
#   - Vision is NOT needed for Phase 1. Phase 1 is kinematics-only simulation.
#   - When adding vision (Phase 2), require AprilTag confirmation before any
#     auto-score action. Abort after 250ms timeout if no tag. Flash LEDs red.
#   - For dual LL4: Camera 1 = always AprilTag. Camera 2 = Hailo NN in auto,
#     switch to AprilTag in teleop via LimelightHelpers.setPipelineIndex().

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ROLE 4: VALIDATION & SAFETY
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Invoke: "As Validation & Safety, ..."
#
# OWNS:
#   - AdvantageKit telemetry consumer wiring (log YAGSL outputs to AK)
#   - CAN bus bandwidth monitoring (target <70% utilization)
#   - Null-pointer safety checks in subsystem initializations
#   - JUnit test generation for kinematic validations
#   - Spotless + SpotBugs enforcement in build.gradle
#   - Auto-score abort logic when no AprilTag is detected (Phase 2)
#
# RULES:
#   - AdvantageKit logs YAGSL telemetry as a CONSUMER. Do NOT create IO interfaces
#     that intercept YAGSL motor commands. Log what YAGSL publishes to NT4.
#   - Use Logger.recordOutput() for custom logged values.
#   - Every subsystem constructor must handle null hardware gracefully for sim.
#   - JUnit tests go in src/test/java/. Test pure math, not hardware.
#   - Test cases for Gate 1.4: pure forward 2m/s, pure rotation 1rad/s,
#     combined strafe-and-rotate. Simulated vs analytical within 2%.
#   - Spotless config: Google Java Format. SpotBugs: medium confidence, fail build.
#   - Never suppress SpotBugs warnings without a code review comment explaining why.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ROLE 5: INTERFACE & DOCS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Invoke: "As Interface & Docs, ..."
#
# OWNS:
#   - Elastic Dashboard layout generation
#   - Addressable LED state mapping with priority animation system
#   - Game manual and rules reference
#   - Single-controller operation design (primary controller on port 0)
#
# RULES:
#   - LED subsystem uses WPILib AddressableLED. Support multiple strips on one port.
#   - Implement priority levels for LED animations:
#       Priority 0 (lowest): Disabled pulse, idle breathing
#       Priority 1: Driving indicators, mode display (coral vs algae)
#       Priority 2: Aligning, intake active
#       Priority 3 (highest): Error/no-tag (red flash), game piece scored (white flash)
#     Higher priority always overrides lower. Same priority = most recent wins.
#   - Minimum LED states for Phase 1:
#       Disabled = slow blue pulse
#       Enabled-idle = solid green
#       Driving = breathing green
#       Aligning = fast yellow blink
#       Error = rapid red flash
#   - Dashboard: publish robot state, module angles, odometry pose via NT4.
#   - Single controller: XboxController port 0. Left stick = translate,
#     right stick X = rotate. Bumpers/triggers for future mechanism control.
#   - All LED patterns must be visible in AdvantageScope or sim console.

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# GLOBAL CODE STANDARDS
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# 1. Java 17. WPILib 2026 command-based framework.
# 2. Package: frc.robot.* for robot code, frc.lib.* for reusable utilities.
# 3. Constants in Constants.java, organized by subsystem inner classes.
# 4. All units in SI (meters, radians, seconds) unless interfacing with
#    hardware that requires other units (YAGSL JSON uses inches for module location).
# 5. No raw Thread usage. Use WPILib's Notifier or CommandScheduler timing.
# 6. Every public method has a Javadoc comment.
# 7. Commit messages: "[Role] Brief description" e.g. "[Drive] Add YAGSL config"
# 8. Test in simulation FIRST. Never deploy untested code to hardware.
# 9. When in doubt, check how 254 (Team254/FRC-2025-Public) or 1678
#    (frc1678/C2025-Public) solved it. Match their quality bar.
#
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# TESTING REQUIREMENTS (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Every feature must include JUnit tests. This is enforced by the Validation &
# Safety agent. When any agent generates a new class or function, the response
# MUST include corresponding test cases in src/test/java/.
#
# TESTING TIERS:
#
# Tier 1 — Pure Math Tests (required for ALL frc.lib.* classes):
#   Every function in frc.lib that takes inputs and returns outputs must have
#   JUnit tests covering: normal case, edge case, and boundary conditions.
#   Target: 90%+ line coverage on frc.lib package.
#   Examples:
#     - AllianceFlip: flip pose, verify mirror
#     - NavigationGrid: load grid, verify cell queries
#     - AStarPathfinder: pathfind around obstacle, verify path avoids it
#     - DynamicAvoidanceLayer: verify force vectors for known opponent positions
#     - Detection zone filtering: in-zone passes, out-of-zone rejected
#     - Bot Aborter math: verify abort threshold calculation
#
# Tier 2 — Subsystem Behavior Tests (required for ALL frc.robot.subsystems.*):
#   Test that subsystems respond correctly to inputs. Use WPILib's simulation
#   hooks where possible. Publish fake data to NetworkTables to test consumers.
#   Target: 50%+ line coverage on frc.robot package.
#   Examples:
#     - LEDs: verify priority override behavior
#     - SwerveSubsystem: verify drive() translates inputs correctly
#     - FuelDetectionConsumer: verify array parsing and persistence filtering
#
# Tier 3 — Integration Tests (required for Phase 3+ autonomous features):
#   Test that multiple components work together in a simulated scenario.
#   These run in WPILib simulation mode.
#   Examples:
#     - Full auto cycle: decision engine → pathfinder → drive → arrive
#     - Vision-gated abort: no tag → abort within 250ms → LED flash
#     - Bot Aborter: opponent approaching → re-target
#
# ENFORCEMENT:
#   - ./gradlew test must pass before any commit
#   - ./gradlew jacocoTestReport generates coverage HTML at
#     build/reports/jacoco/test/html/index.html
#   - Coverage verification on frc.lib enforced at 80% minimum
#   - When generating code, ALWAYS generate tests in the same response.
#     "I'll add tests later" is NOT acceptable.
